### ✅ What are **Callbacks** in JavaScript?

A **callback** is a **function that is passed as an argument to another function** and is **executed later**, usually after some operation is completed.

***

## 🔹 Simple Definition (Interview‑ready)

> A **callback function** is a function passed to another function to be executed after a task completes.

***

## 🔹 Why Callbacks Are Needed

JavaScript is **single‑threaded** and uses **asynchronous operations** for:

*   API calls
*   Timers
*   File reading
*   Event handling

Callbacks allow JavaScript to:
✅ Continue executing code  
✅ Run dependent logic **after** async tasks finish

***

## ✅ Basic Callback Example (Synchronous)

```js
function greet(name, callback) {
  console.log("Hello " + name);
  callback();
}

function sayBye() {
  console.log("Goodbye");
}

greet("Raja", sayBye);
```

### ✅ Output

    Hello Raja
    Goodbye

***

## ✅ Callback Example (Asynchronous)

```js
setTimeout(function () {
  console.log("This runs after 2 seconds");
}, 2000);
```

✅ `setTimeout` takes a **callback function**  
✅ Callback runs **after** delay

***

## ✅ Callbacks with Arrow Functions

```js
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Arrow callback");
}, 1000);
```

✅ Cleaner syntax  
✅ Very common in modern JavaScript

***

## ✅ Real‑World Example: API Call Simulation

```js
function fetchData(callback) {
  setTimeout(() => {
    callback("Data from server");
  }, 2000);
}

fetchData(data => {
  console.log(data);
});
```

### ✅ Output (after 2 seconds)

    Data from server

***

## ✅ Callbacks in Event Handling (Very Important)

```js
button.addEventListener("click", function () {
  console.log("Button clicked");
});
```

✅ Event handlers are callbacks  
✅ Runs **only when event occurs**

***

## ❌ Callback Hell (Major Drawback)

Nested callbacks make code:

*   Hard to read
*   Hard to manage
*   Hard to debug

### ❌ Example (Callback Hell)

```js
getUser(id, function (user) {
  getOrders(user.id, function (orders) {
    getDetails(orders[0], function (details) {
      console.log(details);
    });
  });
});
```

😖 Deep nesting

***

## ✅ Solution to Callback Hell

### ✅ Promises

```js
getUser(id)
  .then(user => getOrders(user.id))
  .then(orders => getDetails(orders[0]))
  .then(details => console.log(details))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

***

### ✅ `async / await`

```js
async function fetchDetails() {
  try {
    const user = await getUser(id);
    const orders = await getOrders(user.id);
    const details = await getDetails(orders[0]);
    console.log(details);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  }
}
```

✅ Cleaner  
✅ Readable  
✅ Modern JavaScript standard

***

## ✅ Callback vs Promise vs async/await

| Feature        | Callback  | Promise  | async/await |
| -------------- | --------- | -------- | ----------- |
| Readability    | ❌ Poor    | ✅ Better | ✅✅ Best     |
| Error handling | ❌ Hard    | ✅ Easy   | ✅ Easy      |
| Chaining       | ❌ No      | ✅ Yes    | ✅ Yes       |
| Modern usage   | ⚠️ Legacy | ✅ Yes    | ✅ Preferred |

***

## ⚠️ Common Interview Traps

### ❓ Are callbacks synchronous?

✅ Can be **both**

*   Sync: array methods
*   Async: `setTimeout`, `fetch`

***

### ❓ Is `setTimeout` callback async?

✅ Yes — callback runs after call stack clears

***

### ❓ Do callbacks block JS execution?

❌ No — async callbacks don’t block the call stack

***

## ✅ Callback Example in Array Methods

```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3];

nums.forEach(function (num) {
  console.log(num);
});
```

✅ `forEach` receives a callback  
✅ Very common interview example

***

## ✅ One‑Line Interview Answer

> A callback is a function passed to another function and executed later, often used to handle asynchronous operations in JavaScript.

***

## ✅ 10‑Second Interview Explanation

> Callbacks allow JavaScript to execute code after an operation completes, especially for async operations like events, timers, and API calls.

***

## ✅ When Callbacks Are Still Used Today

✅ Event listeners  
✅ Array methods  
✅ Legacy code  
✅ Library APIs

